udy. 'And note,' said a plain-looking man who had listened to the whole of the journalist's idea and appreciated it, 'note that Tyutchev's night is cool and the stars in it are round and moist and glossy, and not simply bright dots.' He did not say any more, since in general he spoke little, not so much out of modesty, it seemed, as out of a fear of spilling something precious that was not his but had been entrusted to him. Mrs. Luzhin, incidentally, liked him very much, and precisely because of